Between finding my phone on a regular basis, keeping me aware of the time, helping me remember to finish tasks, and giving me daily compliments, my digital assistant was worth every penny 🥲

My Google home went off during a meeting with a careers guidance counselor today. It told me to not forget to eat as it was noon and to take a break. It tells me that every day, because I sometimes do forget. Counselor was actually pretty impressed and wanted one herself.

This is important as I sometimes feel sluggish and start to beat myself up over not being able to focus, and I won't fully realise it's because of the pills winding down. They are 12 hour slow release, and after about 10 hours the effects wind down.

2) "I'm back"
Volume returns to normal, and Google says "welcome home boss"

3) "I've taken my medication"
The important one. I can't eat for the first hour after I take my morning cocktail. After an hour, it reminds me. After a further 9, it says my ADHD meds are wearing off.

I have implemented 3 new routines for my Google Home.

1) "I'm leaving"
Leaving home lowers the volume, because my daily routine would go off when I'm not there, freaking out my family. Google tells me to come home safe.

(Before lowering the volume obviously)

They are safely taken to a vet where they are checked over, neutered, and then released back to where they were found. You will know if a cat has been TNR'd by a missing eartip, which doesn't effect them at all (both my buds have missing eartips and are entirely unphased)

For those who do not know, TNR stands for Trap Neuter Release, which helps reduce the number of feral kittens born, usually in unsafe conditions, and allows already feral felines to live their best lives without the risk of cat AIDS and pregnancy when still kittens themselves.

Even with more physical ailments - my tiredness and weight aren't due to me being fat and lazy. It's my thyroid failing, and we can work around that. My ankle randomly hurts? Nothing is wrong, it just do be like that coz hyper mobility.
I knew I'd want to play more video games. So I didn't charge my controller. I plugged it in when I started cleaning, so that it would be charged by the time I was done.

The term has been in use since the 40s. We are calling them booster shots because, by definition, it's what they are.

@Agarillobob But it IS a booster. Our immunity has not run out,but it is waning, so it's boosting the immunity. Its why you need to be vaccinated x weeks prior to booster shot being administered. It also helps communicate to the public "regardless of how many previous shots, you need a boost"

Flu vaccines change every year, and we let them run out without boosters because not only do they change to the most probable strains each winter, but we don't need the boost in the summer months. But with COVID we need year long protection. We don't want our immunity to wain.
It boosts the waning protection that we have. It's why you need to have been vaccinated x amount of weeks before you recieve the booster.

For those who may silently be confused, it's not called the third shot because if we recall, not everyone recieved two shots in the first place. Some received the one-and-done vaccine, other immunocompromised people got 3 or more. But everyone needs a booster.

@Agarillobob I preempted this. Not everyone got 2 shots. Some strain of vaccine were one shot. Some who were immunocompromised got 3. Boosters will reinforce and not cause confusion depending on how many shots were administered previously.

@Agarillobob Yeah but the concept of a booster shot predates both of those, I'm pretty sure. The difference is that a booster reinforces an already present vaccine, while flu shots and tetanus shots are new vaccines administered. The flu vaccine for example is new every year.

Aaaand I wanted to get this off my chest as I was thinking about it as my choice to shower (coz I stank) lead me to miss my bus.
(ew you might think - not change a bandage? Often they work as barriers against my clothing more than anything, to prevent rupture and irritation, and well, I'd rather be dirty than in pain)

Know how exhausting showering can be when you're depressed? Imagine all those extra steps added to it. I'm likely as anyone with depression to forgoe simple tasks like showering, and those extra steps make it even harder when I'm low. Or broke (Expensive Bandages tm remember?)

I've typed this all during the "air dry" phase. 

Sometimes, when I've less wounds and my scalp and skin are in better conditions, half of this doesn't matter and I can rush out. But that's never garaunteed.

Then it's time to establish which wounds need the Expensive Bandages tm and which can get away with the cheap ones. Apply any creams for them, put on bandages, ensure they are secure, before I can even consider underwear. I'd hate to be out and discover a bandage has moved.

That's time where I sit in my robe, likely to get distracted by my time blindness. I apply moisturizer on areas unaffected by wounds, because showers dry out my (as established) dry skin to pass the time.

After the shower, it's not as easy as getting dressed and running out the door. Showering means I change my bandages. And I can't apply bandages to wet skin. Gotta be bone dry. And it's best for it to be air dried, to not irritate the wounds further by drying them.

I gotta move slowly in the shower, as I could easily slip. Sure, anyone could, but I'm very likely to break something. Why not get a matt you ask? My mother insisted it be cleaned after each use, adding another tiring step to showering, so, I'd rather just go slow.

Before I shower, I need to apply a dandruff medication and leave it in. My scalp, like much of my skin, is a dry mess. Perpetually. If I don't do this, I'll end up scratching my scalp til it bleeds, or at the very least be incredibly irritated for the next few days.

What people don't realise about disability is that even simple tasks like showering takes so much longer. 
I'm running late and have to host a meeting online because I needed to take a shower. The act used to take 5 minutes. Not anymore and here's why:
